docs.abstract: The quality of synthetic diamonds has increased to the point where they have made their way into jewelry stores, but buyers may lose out in the end.
docs.snippet: The quality of synthetic diamonds has increased to the point where they have made their way into jewelry stores, but buyers may lose out in the end.
docs.lead_paragraph: If you walk into Michaels Jewelers, a family-run chain of jewelry stores in northern Connecticut, to browse the diamond jewelry for a Valentine’s Day gift, you might not notice any difference in the gems. But since last fall, customers there have been given an unusual choice: diamond from below ground or from above it.

headline.main: A Battle Over Diamonds: Made by Nature or in a Lab?
headline.print_headline: A Battle Over Diamonds: Made by Nature or in a Lab?

docs.abstract: It started with an attempt by ABC to reach viewers whom executives at the network felt they had ignored. It ended suddenly, after two months of big ratings and (mostly) welcome headlines.

docs.abstract: The European Union is introducing the G.D.P.R, some of the strictest online privacy rules in the world. The aim is to give internet users more control.
docs.snippet: The European Union is introducing the G.D.P.R, some of the strictest online privacy rules in the world. The aim is to give internet users more control.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — Europe is about to introduce some of the toughest online privacy rules in the world: the General Data Protection Regulation, also known as the G.D.P.R. The changes aim to give internet users more control over what’s collected and shared about them, and they punish companies that don’t comply.

headline.main: What the G.D.P.R., Europe’s Tough New Data Law, Means for You
headline.print_headline: Europe’s Data Rules Get Teeth, And Users Get More Rights

docs.abstract: Media executives watch skeptically as Mark Zuckerberg, in a heated political environment, shifts the focus of his site back to the personal.
docs.snippet: Media executives watch skeptically as Mark Zuckerberg, in a heated political environment, shifts the focus of his site back to the personal.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook’s chief executive, said in an interview with The New York Times on Thursday that he wanted the social network to focus on “meaningful interaction.” But his idea of what that phrase means is likely to differ from that of news industry executives and editors — and therein lies a conflict.

headline.main: The End of the Social News Era? Journalists Brace for Facebook’s Big Change
